</b></p>
<p><b>Persons, Truth and Reconciliation, 2071 (2014) with the international human rights 
</b></p>
<p><b>law.</b> 
</p>
<p><b>  Character of reply: substantive 
</b></p>
<p>64. The Special Rapporteur would like to thank the Government of Nepal for its detailed 
</p>
<p>response to this communication. While recognising the measures taken by the 
</p>
<p>Comprehensive Peace Accord (CPA) and by the Act on Commission on investigation of 
</p>
<p>Disappeared persons, Truth and Reconciliation in 2014, he would like to remind to the 
</p>
<p>Government of Nepal that transitional justice programs should be framed in the context of </p>

<p><b>A/HRC/29/37/Add.5 
</b></p>
<p> <b>37 
</b></p>
<p>the international legal standards obligations, taking into account the view of the national 
</p>
<p>victims. In this regard, the Special Rapporteur invites the Government of Nepal to take 
</p>
<p>further steps to initiate a process of Amendment of the Act, in order to put an end to 
</p>
<p>impunity for the most serious crimes.  
</p>
<p> (c) AL 16/09/2014 Case No. NPL 4/2014 <b>Alleged excessive use of force by the 
</b></p>
